            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Charleston</placeName>, <date>August 10.
                1859</date>.</p>
            <p rend="align(center)"><addressee>Rev. Is.
                    Leeser</addressee>—<placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir—<sic>Inclosed</sic> I send you the continuation<lb/> of “A
                Gala Day” &amp;c. For the II Article on “A Board of<lb/> Deputies” you must await
                another week; I am too<lb/> weak to do more now, for I have just risen from the<lb/>
                sick-bed, having again—as every summer—been visited<lb/> by—inflammatory dysentery.
                Indeed! Only the consideration<lb/> not to have any interception in the first-named
                essay<lb/> could induce me to take up my pen this week; for even<lb/> the mechanical
                work of translating affects me severely.<lb/> I find out more and more every summer,
                that the climate<lb/> of <placeName>Charleston</placeName> is undermining my
                constitution, and I begin<lb/> to think seriously upon a permanent change,
                especially<lb/> as I cannot hope even for leave of absence, as long as<lb/>
                <del>the present</del> our Board of Trustees is constituted as it is<lb/> at
                present. So be not astonished if you should perhaps<lb/> sooner than you might
                expect—hear of my resignation.<lb/> The <placeName>Charleston</placeName> climate is
                certainly none for <hi rend="underline">students</hi>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">How is <persName>Mars</persName>? Why have you not reputed the
                result<lb/> &amp;c. &amp;c. of his first sermon? What is in the wind? Did<lb/> he
                not “<hi rend="underline">take</hi>”? I have my <hi rend="underline">private</hi>
                reasons to ask<lb/> these questions.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Have you seen and read <persName>Dr Kayserling's</persName> work:
                “Sephardim.<lb/> Romanische Poesicen der Juden in Spanien”? For many years, no<lb/>
                work by a Jew has given me more delight than this Book.<lb/> I intend to write of
                course for the <hi rend="underline">Occident</hi>, if welcome to its</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>editor—a very lengthy review, with <add>?</add> extracts upon the<lb/> book. Such a
                book is apt, and ought to create national<lb/> pride in the hearts of all Jews.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I cannot write more now—so <hi rend="underline"
                    >Vale</hi><add>?</add></p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">Yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">M Mayer</persName>
            </p>
